The paper deals with the problem of identifying synaptic partners in neural tissue using high-throughput electron microscopy. This involves segmentation of neurons and identification of pairs of voxels that are pre- and postsynaptic to each other. The proposed method uses a 3D U-Net architecture and formulates the problem as a classification problem on long-range edges between voxels. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category, as it deals with image analysis and segmentation. Additionally, the use of machine learning techniques for classification and the focus on neural networks suggest that the paper may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also involves natural language processing techniques for text classification, which suggests that it may belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Computation and Language (cs.CL) sub-categories.
